  "prompt": "What type of antenna is used in mobile phone receivers?",
  "response": "Mobile phone receivers typically use a type of antenna known as a **microstrip antenna**, also commonly referred to as a **patch antenna**. These antennas are favored due to their compact size, low profile, and ability to be integrated directly onto printed circuit boards, making them ideal for the slim and portable design requirements of modern mobile phones. \n\nMicrostrip antennas consist of a dielectric substrate between a ground plane and a radiating patch, which can be made of conductive materials like copper. The patch can be various shapes such as rectangular, circular, or more complex geometries to optimize performance for specific frequencies and signal reception characteristics.\n\nAdditionally, mobile phones may use **PIFA (Planar Inverted-F Antenna)**, another type of compact antenna suitable for handheld devices, and sometimes incorporate **diversity antennas** to improve reception by mitigating issues like multipath fading.\n\nOverall, these antenna designs work effectively within the constraints of mobile devices, providing adequate signal reception while maintaining the sleek form factor of modern smartphones.",
